<paragraph id="8BAD36E0FFE3FFA5FF781F6B8567F82E" blockId="0.[150,1437,1245,2031]" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FF781F6B80E1FA41" bold="true" box="[199,501,1384,1408]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Diagnosis and description.</emphasis>
Forewing lengths of 
<quantity id="4CEA9B05FFE3FFA5FD611F6B8245FABE" box="[734,849,1384,1407]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="16.0">16–17 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity id="4CEA9B05FFE3FFA5FC371F6B82D8FABE" box="[904,972,1384,1407]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="15.0">15mm</quantity>
for the male and female, respectively. The forewing differs from all other Palearctic congeners being the noctuid maculation lighter reddish-brown, than the ground color and forewing pattern differs by the lower parts of the orbicular and reniform stigmata confluent on the main vein forming a characteristic broad V. The forewing is more similar to four North American specie 
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FB3D1FD38598FA29" bold="true" box="[1154,1164,1488,1512]" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">s</emphasis>
