</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FBFF1FF081DAF9ED" authority="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Crabo" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FBFF1FF08546F9CB" box="[1088,1106,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FBE01FF085ACF9CB" box="[1119,1208,1523,1546]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">gloriosa</emphasis>
Lafontaine &amp; Crabo, 1997
</taxonomicName>
) but can be distinguished by the shape of the crosslines. Compared to the Neartic taxa (
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B11FFE3FFA5FBC71C168426F9ED" author="Lafontaine" box="[1144,1330,1557,1580]" firstAuthor="Lafontaine" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" refId="ref3830" refString="Lafontaine, J. D. (1998) The Moths of America North of Mexico - 27.3 Noctuoidea, Noctuidae (part.). The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation." type="book" year="1998">Lafontaine, 1998</bibRefCitation>
) the male of the new taxon has narrower valvae terminally, a simple non-twisted vesica without subbasal cornutus, and a twin terminal cornutus. In the female genitalia the appendix bursae of 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FCD81C5882D9F9B3" authorityName="Gyulai, Ronkay &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2011" box="[871,973,1627,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspira">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FCD81C5882D9F9B3" box="[871,973,1627,1650]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. aspira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is simple (not coiled) and is considerably smaller than in the four Nearctic species; the shape and sclerotization of ostium bursae is different and the otherwise longer ductus bursae has different sclerotized parts. These genitalic differences also apply to the Palaearctic species, however similarities with 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FE131CC08345F91B" authorityName="Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1775" box="[428,593,1731,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucographa">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FE131CC08345F91B" box="[428,593,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. leucographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
([Denis &amp; Schiffermüller], 1775) including tubular, helicoidally twisted vesica and the lack of a subbasal cornutus indicate a possible grouping with that species. Recent faunistic lists still include 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FA3B1CE5800AF8DE" authorityName="Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucographa">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FA3B1CE5800AF8DE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">C. leucographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FE7F1D0B8211F8DE" authority="Ochsenheimer, 1816" authorityName="Ochsenheimer" authorityYear="1816" box="[448,773,1800,1823]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cerastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FE7F1D0B830DF8DE" box="[448,537,1800,1823]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Cerastis</emphasis>
Ochsenheimer, 1816
</taxonomicName>
but suggestions to put it into a distinct genus began with Heinemann (1859), who established the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FD251D2883D8F883" box="[666,716,1835,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Sora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FD251D2883D8F883" box="[666,716,1835,1858]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Sora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FD411D2882C8F883" authorityName="Denis &amp; Schiffermuller" authorityYear="1775" box="[766,988,1835,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Noctua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucographa">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FD411D2882C8F883" box="[766,988,1835,1858]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Noctua leucographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, suggested it was distinct. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B11FFE3FFA5FF281D4E8034F8A5" author="Tams" box="[151,288,1869,1892]" firstAuthor="Tams" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" pagination="135" refId="ref3901" refString="Tams, W. H. T. (1939) Gypsitea. Entomologist, 72, 135." type="journal article" year="1939">Tams (1939)</bibRefCitation>
stated the homonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FD841D4D8379F8A4" box="[571,621,1870,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Sora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FD841D4D8379F8A4" box="[571,621,1870,1893]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Sora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and gave the replacement name 
<taxonomicName id="4C124D63FFE3FFA5FC671D4D8523F8A4" authorityName="Tams" authorityYear="1939" box="[984,1079,1870,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gypsitea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B966EAF2FFE3FFA5FC671D4D8523F8A4" box="[984,1079,1870,1893]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="46">Gypsitea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B11FFE3FFA5FBCB1D4E85FCF8A5" author="Nye" box="[1140,1256,1869,1892]" firstAuthor="Nye" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" refId="ref3862" refString="Nye, I. W. B. (1975) The Generic Names of the Moths of the World. Vol. 1. Noctuoidea. British Museum (Natural History). London, 568 pp." type="book" year="1975">Nye, 1975</bibRefCitation>
), and both 
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B11FFE3FFA5FADA1D4E81CAF846" author="Beck" firstAuthor="Beck" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" pagination="175 - 232" refId="ref3472" refString="Beck, H. (1992) Taxonomische Anderungen bei den Noctuinae, Cuculliinae und Plusiinae. Atalanta, 22, 175 - 232." type="journal article" year="1992">Beck (1992)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF834B11FFE3FFA5FEAC1D7380BBF846" author="Fibiger" box="[275,431,1904,1927]" firstAuthor="Fibiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 848" refId="ref3568" refString="Fibiger, M. (1997) Noctuidae Europaeae. Volume 3. Noctuinae 3. Entomological Press, Soro. Heinemann, H. (1859): Die Schmetterlinge Deutschlands und der Schweiz: I - XXIII, 1 - 848. Braunschweig. Hemming, F., 1932." type="journal article" year="1997">Fibiger (1997)</bibRefCitation>
considered the possibility of a new taxon. There are clear male genitalic differences between the two allied species: the vesica of the new taxon is not twisted and bears two much shorter and wider basally coincident terminal cornuti, the terminal part of the valva is elongated, the basal part of the harpe is broader, distally thorn-like and dorsally curved, the juxta is differently shaped, and the medial incision is broadly U-formed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
